            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 39-year-old woman with a slender, noticeably thin build, appearing slightly older than her stated age. She presents with a chronic, productive cough, drenching night sweats, and significant unintentional weight loss of approximately 12 kg over the past four months. Her skin shows mild pallor and a few hyperpigmented patches on her forearms. She reports persistent low-grade fevers, profound fatigue, and occasional dyspnea on exertion. Her lymph nodes in the cervical and axillary regions are palpably enlarged bilaterally.\n\n{patientName} grew up in a mid-sized city and currently works part-time as a seamstress from home. She lives in a modest apartment with her two school-aged children (aged 9 and 12), and relies heavily on support from her sister and a close friend who assists with childcare during her frequent medical appointments. Her social circle is small but tight-knit, and she maintains strong ties with a local community health center that has been coordinating her care.\n\nHer daily life has been significantly impacted by her illness. She wakes frequently at night drenched in sweat and struggles to maintain appetite, subsisting largely on soft foods and nutritional supplements. She is a non-smoker and does not use recreational drugs; she drinks alcohol rarely, only on social occasions. She has no regular exercise routine due to fatigue.\n\n{patientName} was diagnosed with HIV infection approximately six years ago following a routine antenatal screen during her second pregnancy. She was started on antiretroviral therapy (ART) but experienced gaps in treatment adherence over the past two years due to financial instability, stigma-related anxiety, and difficulty accessing medications. Her most recent CD4 count was critically low at 68 cells/µL, and HIV RNA viral load was highly elevated. Three months ago, she presented with a persistent cough and fevers; sputum cultures eventually confirmed Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC) infection consistent with her current diagnosis of B20.0.\n\n{patientName} is generally cooperative and motivated to re-engage with care. She expresses guilt about gaps in her ART adherence but is now committed to resuming a structured treatment regimen. She regularly attends a patient support group for women living with HIV and finds it emotionally beneficial. Her primary concerns are protecting her children from her illness and returning to a functional daily routine."
