            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with HIV-1 infection six years ago at age 33, identified incidentally during antenatal screening. She was linked to care and initiated on antiretroviral therapy (ART) with good initial virological response. However, over the past two years she experienced two prolonged gaps in ART adherence due to socioeconomic hardship, medication access difficulties, and psychosocial stressors including depression and HIV-related stigma.\n\nShe has no prior history of tuberculosis or prior AIDS-defining illnesses. She has a history of mild iron-deficiency anemia managed with oral supplementation. She experienced one episode of oral candidiasis approximately 18 months ago, which was treated with a short course of fluconazole. She has no history of diabetes, hypertension, or cardiovascular disease. She had a caesarean section during her second pregnancy (2015) without complications.\n\nHer most recent CD4+ T-cell count was 68 cells/µL (down from 340 cells/µL three years ago), and her HIV RNA viral load is currently >500,000 copies/mL. Sputum and blood cultures confirmed Mycobacterium avium complex. A chest X-ray showed bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy and patchy infiltrates. Liver function tests revealed elevated alkaline phosphatase. She has no known drug allergies on record at presentation, though a penicillin allergy was reported verbally.\n\nShe is currently a non-smoker, does not use illicit substances, and drinks alcohol infrequently. She takes no over-the-counter medications regularly except occasional paracetamol for fever and headache. She has two children (both HIV-negative, confirmed by neonatal testing) aged 9 and 12, and lives in a low-income urban setting. She is not currently in a relationship."
